OWASP Security Principle	Purpose	Key Requirements / Controls	Example
Minimize Attack Surface Area	Reduce the number of possible attack points.	• Disable unused services
• Remove unnecessary features
• Close unused ports
• Limit exposed APIs	A web server only exposes ports 80 and 443 instead of every open port.
Principle of Least Privilege	Give users and applications only the permissions they need.	• Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)
• Separate admin/user accounts
• Time-limited privileges
• Regular permission reviews	A customer account cannot access the admin dashboard.
Defense in Depth	Use multiple layers of security instead of relying on one control.	• Firewalls
• MFA
• Endpoint protection
• IDS/IPS
• Encryption	Even if a password is stolen, MFA prevents unauthorized access.
Fail Securely	If something fails, it should fail in a secure state.	• Default deny access
• Graceful error handling
• No sensitive error messages	If authentication fails, the user is denied access rather than being logged in accidentally.
Secure by Default	Systems should be secure without requiring users to enable security features.	• Strong default settings
• Disabled unnecessary services
• Default-deny configurations	A new application requires HTTPS by default.
Separation of Duties	Divide responsibilities so no single person has complete control.	• Dual approval
• Administrative separation
• Change management	One employee submits a code change while another reviews and approves it.
Keep Security Simple	Simple systems are easier to understand, maintain, and secure.	• Clear code
• Simple configurations
• Avoid unnecessary complexity	A simple authentication flow is easier to audit than a highly customized one.
Fix Security Issues Correctly	Solve the root cause instead of applying temporary fixes.	• Root cause analysis
• Secure coding practices
• Regression testing	Developers fix the vulnerable SQL query rather than filtering only one malicious input.
Don't Trust External Systems	Treat all external input and systems as untrusted.	• Input validation
• Output encoding
• API validation
• Third-party verification	A web application validates every form submission before processing it.
Security as a Business Requirement	Security should be built into every stage of development and operations.	• Security requirements
• Threat modeling
• Secure SDLC
• Risk assessments	Security reviews are required before new software is deployed.
